/**
 * The Color function can be used to define colors, either as a string value or as an object. All colors are converted to a Color object with `r, g, b`, `h, s, l` and an `a` value. There are also various helpers on the Color function for working with, modifying and detecting colors.
 * ```typescript
 * // HEX
 * const blue = Color("#28AFFA")
 *
 * // RGB
 * const blue = Color("rgb(255, 0, 102)")
 * const blue = Color(255, 0, 102, 255})
 * const blue = Color({r: 255, g: 0, b: 102})
 * const blue = Color({r: 255, g: 0, b: 102, a: 255})
 *
 * // HSL
 * const blue = Color("hsl(201, 95, 57)")
 * const blue = Color({h: 201, s: 95, l: 57})
 * const blue = Color({h: 201, s: 95, l: 57, a: 1})

/**
 * Blend two colors together, optionally based on user input. The fraction defines the distribution between the two colors, and is set to 0.5 by default.
 *
 * @remarks
 * ```typescript
 * // Mix red with yellow
 * const orange = Color.mix("red", "yellow", 0.5)
 * ```
 *
 * The `limit` defines if the color can transition beyond its range. This is applicable when transitioning between colors, using Utils.modulate. Below, the limit is set to `true`, so the transition cannot extend beyond the second color.
 * ```typescript
 * fraction = Utils.modulate(offset.x, [0, window.outerWidth], [0, 1], true)
 * Color.mix("red", "yellow", fraction, true, "husl")
 * ```
 *
 * @param colorA - A color, the first one.
 *
 * @param colorB - A color, the second one.
 *
 * @param fraction - An optional number, from 0 to 1, set to 0.5 by default.
 *
 * @param limit - An optional boolean, set to false by default.
 *
 * @param model - The model to use for the mix. One of {@link ColorMixModelType}

/**
 * A control that can be used to take a single number or four distinct fields. These will be mapped across six associated props.
 *
 * @remarks
 *
 * The canonical example for this control is for border, padding or margin control. It will display an input field to accept a single value and a segmented control allowing values to be provided for four distinct fields. A boolean prop can be used in code to determine whether the single or multi input field was used.
 * ```typescript
 * interface Props {
 *   isPerSide: boolean
 *   border: number
 *   top: number
 *   left: number
 *   right: number
 *   bottom: number
 * }
 * static propertyControls: PropertyControls<Props> = {
 *   title: {
 *     type: ControlType.FusedNumber,
 *     // Optional default value for each field.
 *     defaultValue: 0,
 *     // The prop that determines whether the single or multi value input was used.
 *     toggleKey: "isPerSide",
 *     // The individual props to map the values to.
 *     valueKeys: ["top", "left", "right", "bottom"],
 *     // Labels for each of the fields.
 *     valueLabels: ["T", "L", "R", "B"],
 *     // Optional minimum value for each field.
 *     min: 0,
 *   },
 * }
 * ```
 *
 */
members.name: FusedNumber
